(123, ' Salams Wampyr, I thought it would be more appropriate if we continue the discussion here and other members can also get to know your contribution to the page.\n\nI''m glad the website is taking shape. My aim was to keep the main page under 75k which I managed with the current site.\n\nAs far as the test site that you sent me. It was good! I really liked the flash part, that is a fantastic idea and looks excellent. Since I want to stick with the current layout for a while I''ve been trying to visualize where we could fit a proper version of that animation in the current site without making the webpage slow. The only place it would fit and look good is if we make the logo part of the animation. As soon as the page loads, the normal ''two pistols'' logo displays for 5 seconds and then the flash animation starts from there and runs about 5 guns like you made it and ends at the logo again.\n\nHow can we make that happen while keeping the size small ?', ''),
(124, ' Hi Acciprone and welcome ! \n\nI think all the Turkish shotguns are more or less the same, the pump actions range from 30 k to 55 k depending on finish and accessories and the repeaters / semi''s range from 45 k to 85 k as you mentioned. They are decent enough performers for light use as I have personally never heard of anything going wrong with anyone''s Turk Shotgun. Talking of Germanica btw I once caught a shopkeeper try to selling two gun noobs a Germanica for a 115 K convincing them about it being made in ITALY under GERMAN supervision, I was shocked at how much he was trying to rip them off as that was clearly a Turkish import. Btw the original Germanicas were made in Italy under Germanica license before it was discontinued as a model. The Turks bought the failed label and stuck it on every half decent shotgun they manufactured. \n\nThe difference between about 95 % of Turkish imports is the accessories. Some come with two barrels, (20'' inch for self defense and 28'' for hunting) more chokes, better stocks etc but in the end it''s the same product with cosmetic variations.\n\nI''m sorry I don''t really understand your question about the stock, did you mean how to remove a fixed long stock and put in a pistol grip ? If so then all you need to do if look at the shoulder end of your gun, if you look closely you will see two screws, open them, the stock back will open, the stock itself will be hollow and another screw will be holding the stock fixed to the gun, open that and the stock comes off. The pistol grip is just a matter of holding it in place and screwing it in.\n\nYou said folding butt also so I''m confused, a folding butt generally has a button that you press and hold down and the full stock opens.\n\nThe third and last thing is how to remove a pistol grip folding stock. That is the simplest. There is usually a big screw on the top back side of the pistol grip, open that with a big screw driver and replace with the long fixed stock like I told you to remove above only backwards..\n\nHope it helps.', ''),
